<br>
Problem with this enlies in situations like this:<br>
<br>
Guild raids uhh, some random dragon.<br>
<br>
RBG drops.  WarriorA, who has been a longtime member of the guild, who has attended many, many dragon raids and has lost all of the rolls, is still in an FBSS.  WarriorB, who is wearing Some_No_Drop_Uber_Haste_Item_1%_less_haste_than_RBG, has only been in the guild one week, and rarely attends raids.  They both roll.  WarriorA loses to WarriorB.<br>
<br>
A few days later, WarriorB has quit the guild and is seen auctioning the RBG in EC.<br>
<br>
Moral of the story:  Open roll sucks.  The only thing you are achieving by advocating this way of deciding loot is making yourself look like a loot whore.<br>
<br>
However, I am a skeptic of the system Vision uses.  I do think there are better ways to handle loot than to have it decided between one person or a group of people.  Just too many issues such as favoritism, or a certain class officer not being online at the time, and there's no possible way these people are going to know every single member of the guild well.  But, it is still a much better system than others, and the majority of the members of Vision feel that it works for them just fine.  I imagine most members of Vision trust their officers with this power, and feel that they will make good decisions.<br>
<br>
This system, as well as the 'point system' benefit the guild much as a whole.  The point system especially, makes sure that items go to a person who is definitely going to put it to use the most.  If you're often going to raids, you're going to get a lot of points towards loot.  It's not very good handing a Paladin a CoF who only logs in once a month, as he's not going to put it to much use.  Additionally, it encourages members to attend raids in which they have no shot at loot, such as a Wizard at a guild raid for the first floor of PoH:  nothing drops for them there (I think).  However, rather than possibly being bored, they know they can get points for attending this raid.<br>
<br>
However, bottom line:  If you don't like the loot rules, you don't have to join Vision.  It seems to work for Vision just fine.<br>
<br>
Oh, and bottom line#2:<br>
<br>
